## 1. Purpose
This policy ensures that changes to [COMPANY]'s production systems — including the SaaS application, [AWS] infrastructure, [Snowflake], and CI/CD configuration — are authorized, tested, peer-reviewed, and traceable, so that changes do not degrade the confidentiality, integrity, or availability of systems handling Protected Health Information (PHI). It exists to prevent unauthorized, untested, or unilateral changes from reaching production.

## 2. Scope
Applies to all changes to in-scope production systems and the data they process, including application code, infrastructure-as-code (IaC), database schemas and [Snowflake] objects, CI/CD pipeline definitions, IAM and security configurations, and third-party integrations. It covers all workforce members and contractors with the ability to author, review, approve, or deploy such changes. Local development and ephemeral non-production environments are out of scope except where a change is promoted from them toward production.

## 3. Policy
1. Every change to a production system **shall** be tracked in [GitHub] as a pull request (PR) linked to a ticket or issue describing the rationale, scope, and risk.
2. Changes **shall** be classified as **Standard** (pre-approved, low-risk, repeatable), **Normal** (requires review and approval through the standard workflow), or **Emergency** (required to restore service or remediate an active security/availability incident) — see §5.
3. **Separation of duties shall be enforced: the author of a change shall not be its sole approver, and shall not approve their own change.** At least [1] independent qualified reviewer **shall** approve every Normal change before merge. Where feasible, the person who deploys a change **shall not** be the sole author of it.
4. All changes **shall** pass required automated checks (build, automated tests, and the security gates defined in `secure-sdlc-policy.md.template`) before merge; checks **shall not** be bypassable by the author.
5. Changes **shall** be tested in a non-production environment representative of production before promotion, proportionate to risk. Production data containing PHI **shall not** be copied into test environments (see `secure-sdlc-policy.md.template`).
6. Every change **shall** have a documented rollback or recovery plan (revert, redeploy of prior version, or restore) before deployment to production.
7. Production deployments **shall** be performed through automated, auditable pipelines using short-lived credentials (OIDC to AWS), not manual changes with long-lived keys, except under the Emergency path with subsequent reconciliation.
8. Direct pushes to protected branches **shall** be prohibited; production-impacting branches **shall** be protected with required reviews and required status checks (see §6).
9. Emergency changes **shall** follow the expedited path in §7 and **shall** be retroactively reviewed and documented within [2 business days].
10. A complete, tamper-evident record of who authored, approved, and deployed each change **shall** be retained per `logging-and-monitoring-policy.md.template`.

## 4. Roles & Responsibilities
| Role | Responsibility |
|---|---|
| [Engineering Lead] | Owns this policy; defines change classifications; ensures branch protection and pipeline controls are configured. |
| Change Author | Raises the PR/ticket, documents rationale and rollback, ensures tests pass. |
| Change Reviewer / Approver | Independently reviews for correctness, security, and operational risk; cannot be the author. |
| Deployer / Release Manager | Executes the deployment via the approved pipeline; verifies post-deploy health. |
| [Security Officer] | Reviews that change controls satisfy ISMS and HITRUST requirements; reviews emergency changes. |
| [CTO] | Approves this policy; authorizes high-risk or freeze-window changes. |

See `../governance/roles-and-responsibilities.md.template` for full role definitions.

## 5. Change Types
| Type | Definition | Approval |
|---|---|---|
| Standard | Pre-approved, low-risk, well-understood and repeatable (e.g., routine dependency bump passing all gates). | Pre-authorized change template; still requires independent merge approval and passing checks. |
| Normal | Default. Any non-trivial change to production. | At least [1] independent reviewer + all required checks pass. High-risk changes may require [Engineering Lead] or [CTO] sign-off. |
| Emergency | Needed to restore service or remediate an active incident where the normal path would cause unacceptable delay. | Verbal/async approval by [on-call lead / Engineering Lead]; retroactive review per §7. |

